What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183,412 bike ride logs in the dataset with 16 features (duration, start and end of the trip, start and end stations name, coordinates, and id, bike id and user details – type of user subscription, if the subscriber is enrolled in the Share for all program and the user’s year of birth and gender. Most variables are numeric in nature (year, coordinates, ids), and some are categorical: gender, type of user, station name. The time measures (start and finish of the trip) are strings, so will need to be converted.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out if there are any patterns in the characteristics and behavior of the users that will impact the demand at a certain moment in time. I find this important because, as a service provider, you need to know when are your peeks in the demand so you make sure the bikes are available to the customers. So, I will add a measure that specifies the minute of the day that a trip starts.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect the location will have an impact and also the user type, age and gender. This is because older people are retired so they might use a bike for leisure, middle age and young people might use the bikes for commuting to work. Subscribers might have a more predictable pattern of renting – I expect the subscribers are professionals or students commuting. Also, if you have a long commute, you will need to pick up a bike earlier so you reach the destination in time. I will need to transform the database in order to have these details, but I will start from the year of birth, the coordinates of stations, the user types and gender.

First step is to cleanup and transform the data:

Discuss the data cleanup and transformation. Did you find any issues with the data?¶

In order to have the measures I wanted to explore structured I added extra columns:

  • Moment of trip start and end (minute of the day)
  • Day of the month
  • Day of the week
  • A label as working week or weekend
  • Difference in days between start and end of trip
  • Location cluster name of start and end – there are 3 major cities.
  • Age as difference between 2019 and the year of birth

I also cleaned some records:

  • Removed rows with missing data
  • Age higher than 80 – around 8- records, as some years of birth were whether typos (1978 instead of 1978) or the default 1900; some probably are valid records, but since there are not many I decided are not representative.
  • Dropped the trips between clusters – 8 because are exceptions.
  • Merged the “Share for all” label into the user type column so I have a single measure that has values : Customer, Subscriber (regular that is), and ‘Bike4All” (subscriber with a special discount)
  • Removed trips that started in one day and ended the next day after 6AM as this means the user kept the bike overnight - the duration is not a trip duration per se.
  • Set the location and week day flag (work week or weekend) as ordered categorical in order to have consistency when plotting.

The duration variable took on a large range of values, so I plotted the data using a log transform. I created the labels for readability: ticks([60, 180,600, 900, 1800, 3600, 36000, 90000], ['1m','3m','10m', '15m','30m','1h', '10h', '25h'])

Also, for the start of day I labeled based on clock values: ticks([360,500,720,900,1100,1320], ['6','8:30','12', '15','18:30','22'])

# compute the logarithm of the duration to make multivariate plotting easier
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ quick function for computing log and power operations """
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)

bike2['log_duration'] = bike2['duration_sec'].apply(log_trans)

# define a function that plots heat maps as a matrix/grid for duration and start of the trip
def hist2dgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating heat maps with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    palette = kwargs.pop('color')
    bins_y=np.arange(0,1500,100)
    bins_x=np.arange(np.log10(60),np.log10(3700),(np.log10(1800)-np.log10(900))/3)
    plt.hist2d(x, y, bins=[bins_x,bins_y], cmap = palette, cmin = 0.5)
    plt.xticks([np.log10(60), np.log10(180),np.log10(600),np.log10(900), np.log10(1800), np.log10(3600)], ['1m','3m', '10m','15m','30m','1h'])
    plt.yticks([360,500,720,900,1100,1320], ['6','8:30','12', '15','18:30','22'])

These two views wrap up the most important findings – location is important because the demographics are essentials in each of the 2 cities and it’s the needs of the users that dictate the peaks in demand.

For San Francisco we have mostly Subscribers, with a median age in their early 30s that are driving the peek in demands at 8:30 and 18:30. For San Jose we have mostly discount subscribers that mostly in their late 20’s and they do not drive peaks in demand during the day (whether is work day or weekend).

There are also customers without subscription – the ones in San Francisco have a behavior and age distribution similar to the regular subscribers; In Oakland they seem more like the discount subscribers. In San Jose they are a very rare.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

In this part of the investigation I wanted to put together the hints I got from the previous views – I wanted to see the dynamics of users in each city – what are their ages and what trips do they take and when.

The combined heatmaps revealed how, during workweeks, in San Jose we have trips done mostly by young discount subscribers in their 20’s that are renting bikes all day long but in San Francisco and Oakland we have trips done mostly by subscribers with a higher median age (in their 30’s) that probably use the bike share service to commute towards work and back. The weekend has an effect of leveling the demand during the day in all cities.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I found it very striking the difference between San Jose customer base and the other 2 cities – especially San Francisco. I imagine the San Francisco has a higher standard of living and the users are mainly professionals as opposed to the other two where there is either a lower standard of living or there are more university student subscribers. I will have to do some research on this topic.
